text: This character has been betrayed.  Is she supposed to smile and sing-song her way through it? lol Besides that,  I can tell the deepies who are griping about "another angry black woman movie" are not watching anything much more than what they are spoon-fed.  There are plenty of positive "non-angry" black women movies out every year.  Sure, many of them are independent films which don't have big budget machines behind them,  but they're still out here. We just had a major one with...oh look...TARAJI (Hidden Figures). The more uplifting movies are readily available for streaming on apps such as Netflix, and even right here on Youtube. Go watch them.  Having said that, I'm seeing this and I'm going to enjoy it. Ion curr.  It looks good.  Sure, it's predictable and we've seen it before, but it still looks very exciting, Taraji is in it, and a little "fluff" has never killed anyone.

text: Saw it today. Of course,Taraji is fascinating as always. However, the film is, indeed, "a stereotype of the angry black woman" as Taraji's character says she hopes you will understand she isn't. Fail! Why the heck would Tyler Perry do this to women? Basically, it's about  a mentally ill person - bipolar, paranoid, depressed, rageaholic - whatever diagnosis you want to fill in for yourself. So in a way there's not true "back story" to give her a motive for reacting kray-kray over everything, large and small, that she perceives has been "done" to her. She's just another vengeful sicko. It would be a tragedy except that it's so over the top improbable and, consequently, silly. The husband here is not particularly heinous. Yes, he's an impractical dreamer who doesn't have it together financially for many years as he tries to make a Shark Tank breakthrough with his tech idea. And yes, he cheated on her once in their 'teens (for which she forgave him and even followed up by marrying him). But he didn't seem like a major cheating type, he did not abuse her and he professed, always, to love her. For me, he was the scapegoat for all her pent up rage at her intolerant, judgmental family. And that made for a very weak film. Still, Taraji is, after all, HER, and she's going to be a magnet in any movie. Still, I felt let down by Perry, because he seemed to have made a film that depicts a woman as a scorned lunatic. Darn it. Another wall to break down.
